✅ Step 2: Nested Field Resolvers
What we built

Schema:

type User {
    id: ID!
    name: String!
    age: Int!
    posts: [Post!]!
}

type Post {
    id: ID!
    title: String!
    content: String!
}

We forced gqlgen to generate

func (r *userResolver) Posts(ctx context.Context, obj *model.User) ([]*model.Post, error)

using

models:
  User:
    fields:
      posts:
        resolver: true
What actually happens internally

When the client executes

query {
    users {
        id
        name
        posts {
            content
        }
    }
}

GraphQL does not fetch everything at once.

Instead, execution happens like a tree traversal.

                 Query
                   │
                   ▼
             users()
                   │
                   ▼
        ┌───────────────┐
        │               │
      User1          User2
        │               │
        ▼               ▼
 Posts(User1)     Posts(User2)
        │               │
        ▼               ▼
   Post1 Post2     Post3 Post4
Actual execution
Step 1

GraphQL calls

Users()

which returns

[]User{
    John,
    Jane,
}
Step 2

GraphQL now starts resolving every requested field.

For User 1

Posts(ctx, John)

Notice

obj == John

For User 2

Posts(ctx, Jane)

Now

obj == Jane

Inside your resolver

switch obj.ID {

case "1":
    ...

case "2":
    ...
}

GraphQL already knows which user is being processed.

That's why it passes

obj *model.User

instead of

userID string
The important realization

GraphQL is traversing a graph.

It is literally saying

I already have this User.

Now tell me about its Posts.

It is not

Go search for some random posts.

This is why the resolver signature is

Posts(ctx, obj *model.User)

instead of

Posts(userID string)
Why field resolvers exist

Imagine PostgreSQL.

Users table

id
name
age

Posts table

id
title
content
user_id

Your Users resolver executes

SELECT *
FROM users;

It returns

John
Jane

There are no posts yet.

Later GraphQL asks

Resolve John's posts.

Now your resolver runs

SELECT *
FROM posts
WHERE user_id = 1;

Then

Resolve Jane's posts.
SELECT *
FROM posts
WHERE user_id = 2;

That is exactly how production GraphQL servers work.

Difference from REST

REST usually looks like

GET /users

↓

GET /users/1/posts

↓

GET /users/2/posts

The client decides which endpoints to call.

GraphQL instead receives

{
    users {
        posts {
            title
        }
    }
}

and the GraphQL server decides which resolvers to invoke to satisfy that single query.

